<paragraph id="5F0EF629EA060C13FF4DFC14F4EE56C1" blockId="25.[151,1436,848,1880]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis id="6DC52A3BEA060C13FF4DFC14F09A50C8" bold="true" box="[198,488,965,991]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Diagnostic description.</emphasis>
Body reddish brown, shining. Length of pronotum + elytra = 3.2 mm (male), 3.5–3.6 mm (females). Head finely, sparsely punctate. Pronotum widest at basal two-fifths; sides strongly, roundly angulate at basal two-fifths; basal angles obsolete; with fringe of elongate setae laterally; ratio length:width = 1:1.4; finely, sparsely punctate with no visible microsculpture. Elytra wider than pronotum, with fringe of elongate setae laterally; ratio length:width = 1:0.7; with 9 regular, closely punctate striae; stria 1 clearly impressed, remaining striae weakly or not impressed; intervals minutely punctate; uneven intervals with scattered larger punctures. Antennal club (
<figureCitation id="C78AEAACEA060C13FD35FB7CF26157D0" box="[702,787,1197,1223]" captionStart="FIGURES 62–67" captionStartId="26.[151,271,1318,1342]" captionTargetBox="[242,1350,200,1285]" captionTargetId="figure-224@26.[232,1356,197,1291]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURES 62–67. Stereus arenarius. 62. Male right antenna, dorsal view. 63. Mandibles, dorsal view. 64. Male right metafemur and metatibia. 65. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 66. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 67. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Figs. 63, 67), 0.4 mm (Figs. 62, 65), 0.5 mm (Fig. 66), 0.75 mm (Fig. 64)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310929" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310929/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 62</figureCitation>
) broad, ratio club width:length = 1:2.0; antennomeres 7 and 8 equal in width, width ratio of antennomeres 6:7:8:9 = 1:1.5:1.5:2.8; antennomere 9 strongly asymmetrical. Terminal antennomere with a narrow, glabrous apical ridge. Mandibles (
<figureCitation id="C78AEAACEA060C13FB1AFB2BF5945603" box="[1169,1254,1274,1300]" captionStart="FIGURES 62–67" captionStartId="26.[151,271,1318,1342]" captionTargetBox="[242,1350,200,1285]" captionTargetId="figure-224@26.[232,1356,197,1291]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURES 62–67. Stereus arenarius. 62. Male right antenna, dorsal view. 63. Mandibles, dorsal view. 64. Male right metafemur and metatibia. 65. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 66. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 67. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Figs. 63, 67), 0.4 mm (Figs. 62, 65), 0.5 mm (Fig. 66), 0.75 mm (Fig. 64)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310929" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310929/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 63</figureCitation>
) elongate, with elongate, narrow apices; left mandible with a tooth on apical one-half of inner margin. Profemur and mesofemur unarmed in both sexes; metafemur robust in both sexes, in male (
<figureCitation id="C78AEAACEA060C13FBD1FA99F5C55675" box="[1114,1207,1352,1378]" captionStart="FIGURES 62–67" captionStartId="26.[151,271,1318,1342]" captionTargetBox="[242,1350,200,1285]" captionTargetId="figure-224@26.[232,1356,197,1291]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURES 62–67. Stereus arenarius. 62. Male right antenna, dorsal view. 63. Mandibles, dorsal view. 64. Male right metafemur and metatibia. 65. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 66. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 67. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Figs. 63, 67), 0.4 mm (Figs. 62, 65), 0.5 mm (Fig. 66), 0.75 mm (Fig. 64)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310929" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310929/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 64</figureCitation>
), posterior margin serrulate. Protibia of both sexes widened at apex, with rounded lobe at outer margin; dorsal surface with shallow tarsal depression. Mesotibia of both sexes widened at apex. Metatibia of male (
<figureCitation id="C78AEAACEA060C13FB3BFA44F47556B8" box="[1200,1287,1429,1455]" captionStart="FIGURES 62–67" captionStartId="26.[151,271,1318,1342]" captionTargetBox="[242,1350,200,1285]" captionTargetId="figure-224@26.[232,1356,197,1291]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURES 62–67. Stereus arenarius. 62. Male right antenna, dorsal view. 63. Mandibles, dorsal view. 64. Male right metafemur and metatibia. 65. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 66. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 67. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Figs. 63, 67), 0.4 mm (Figs. 62, 65), 0.5 mm (Fig. 66), 0.75 mm (Fig. 64)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310929" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310929/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 64</figureCitation>
) and female widened at apex, spurs enlarged, spatulate. All tibiae of both sexes spinose on outer margin. Protarsi slender.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5F0EF629EA060C13FF1CFA33F2FE5567" blockId="25.[151,1436,848,1880]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis id="6DC52A3BEA060C13FF1CFA33F19256EB" bold="true" box="[151,224,1506,1532]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Male.</emphasis>
Aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="C78AEAACEA060C13FEFEFA33F0A356EB" box="[373,465,1506,1532]" captionStart="FIGURES 62–67" captionStartId="26.[151,271,1318,1342]" captionTargetBox="[242,1350,200,1285]" captionTargetId="figure-224@26.[232,1356,197,1291]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURES 62–67. Stereus arenarius. 62. Male right antenna, dorsal view. 63. Mandibles, dorsal view. 64. Male right metafemur and metatibia. 65. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 66. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 67. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Figs. 63, 67), 0.4 mm (Figs. 62, 65), 0.5 mm (Fig. 66), 0.75 mm (Fig. 64)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310929" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310929/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 65</figureCitation>
) with median lobe broad, evenly tapering to rounded apex. Parameres extend beyond apex of median lobe, slender, apices concave medially, with two short setae. 
<emphasis id="6DC52A3BEA060C13FB1FF9D9F5855535" bold="true" box="[1172,1271,1544,1570]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Female.</emphasis>
Coxites (
<figureCitation id="C78AEAACEA060C13FAE7F9D8F1C4555D" captionStart="FIGURES 62–67" captionStartId="26.[151,271,1318,1342]" captionTargetBox="[242,1350,200,1285]" captionTargetId="figure-224@26.[232,1356,197,1291]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURES 62–67. Stereus arenarius. 62. Male right antenna, dorsal view. 63. Mandibles, dorsal view. 64. Male right metafemur and metatibia. 65. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 66. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 67. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Figs. 63, 67), 0.4 mm (Figs. 62, 65), 0.5 mm (Fig. 66), 0.75 mm (Fig. 64)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310929" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310929/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 67</figureCitation>
) moderately elongate, cylindrical; styli elongate, inserted at apices of coxites. Sternite 8 (
<figureCitation id="C78AEAACEA060C13FB51F9E1F443555D" box="[1242,1329,1584,1610]" captionStart="FIGURES 62–67" captionStartId="26.[151,271,1318,1342]" captionTargetBox="[242,1350,200,1285]" captionTargetId="figure-224@26.[232,1356,197,1291]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURES 62–67. Stereus arenarius. 62. Male right antenna, dorsal view. 63. Mandibles, dorsal view. 64. Male right metafemur and metatibia. 65. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 66. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 67. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Figs. 63, 67), 0.4 mm (Figs. 62, 65), 0.5 mm (Fig. 66), 0.75 mm (Fig. 64)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310929" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310929/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 66</figureCitation>
) weakly, broadly triangular at apex; anterior apophysis broadly triangular.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="17ABA5A2EA060C13FF4DF9ACF5265425" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="5F0EF629EA060C13FF4DF9ACF0BC55A9" blockId="25.[151,1436,848,1880]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis id="6DC52A3BEA060C13FF4DF9ACF0155580" bold="true" box="[198,359,1661,1687]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Distribution.</emphasis>
The species is known only from 
<collectingRegion id="9D7538CBEA060C13FD75F9ACF2245580" box="[766,854,1661,1687]" country="Canada" name="Alberta" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Alberta</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion id="9D7538CBEA060C13FC1FF9ACF5735580" box="[916,1025,1661,1687]" country="United States of America" name="Colorado" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Colorado</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation id="C78AEAACEA060C13FB9FF9ACF51F5580" box="[1044,1133,1661,1687]" captionStart="FIGURE 68" captionStartId="27.[151,257,1226,1250]" captionTargetBox="[224,1363,197,1200]" captionTargetId="figure-207@27.[224,1363,197,1200]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 68. Known North American localities of Stereus arenarius (asterisks), Sogda obtusa (black dots), Sogda enigma (open squares)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310933" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310933/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 68</figureCitation>
), but may be assumed to occur in intervening areas.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5F0EF629EA060C13FF4DF91BF559541C" blockId="25.[151,1436,848,1880]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis id="6DC52A3BEA060C13FF4DF91BF08D55F3" bold="true" box="[198,511,1738,1764]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Field notes and habitats.</emphasis>
The preferred habitats seem to be sand dunes or sandy areas, based on label data, and the modifications of the tibiae, which seem to be adapted to digging.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5F0EF629EA060C13FF4DF8C6F5265425" blockId="25.[151,1436,848,1880]" box="[198,1108,1815,1842]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis id="6DC52A3BEA060C13FF4DF8C6F0285426" bold="true" box="[198,346,1815,1841]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Seasonality.</emphasis>
Adults of the species are known only from the month of August.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="17ABA5A2EA060C13FF4DF8EFF4E9544F" box="[198,1435,1854,1880]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="5F0EF629EA060C13FF4DF8EFF4E9544F" blockId="25.[151,1436,848,1880]" box="[198,1435,1854,1880]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis id="6DC52A3BEA060C13FF4DF8EFF021544F" bold="true" box="[198,339,1854,1880]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name is Latin, 
<emphasis id="6DC52A3BEA060C13FDB6F8EEF3F2544F" box="[573,640,1855,1880]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">arena</emphasis>
, for sand, referring to the assumed preferred habitat for the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
